# The build cache

`LoomMemo` is the incremental build cache ‚Äî the reason editing one `.loom` does not recompile the project. Building a module ‚Äî parsing it, then composing its product ‚Äî is the costly half; projecting it afterwards is cheap. So a keystroke stays cheap by not rebuilding what did not change: each module is built once, kept by path, and returned on the next request. It is deliberately just a `path ‚Üí LoomModule` cache ‚Äî it knows nothing of imports, so which paths an edit invalidates stays the compiler's call, handed to `evict`.

## The observable state

`MemoStats` is the window onto the cache: hits against misses is the work an edit avoided, and size is how many modules are kept. The state holds the kept modules and the running tallies immutably behind a `SynchronizedRef`, and `empty` is its starting value.

=>

export interface MemoStats {
  readonly hits: number
  readonly misses: number
  readonly size: number
}

interface MemoState {
  readonly modules: ReadonlyMap<Path, LoomModule>
  readonly hits: number
  readonly misses: number
}

const empty: MemoState = { modules: new Map(), hits: 0, misses: 0 }

## The cache as a service

`LoomMemo` is that cache as a service ‚Äî one instance is the project's build cache. `get` is a hit (return the kept module) or a miss (run `build`, keep it, count it), checked and built in one atomic step so a module builds at most once under concurrent gets. The `build` it runs may itself `get` the cache for its imports. `entries` exposes the kept modules for the compiler to project and to walk. `evict` forgets a set of paths by copy-and-change, never mutating the kept map. `stats` reports the counters.

`get` caches each module whole ‚Äî its parse and its `product` together ‚Äî since `LoomCorpusAstBuilder` builds both in one pass. `fill` keeps the cache consistent with a full build: after running the whole corpus, the compiler hands `fill` the produced modules, and each overwrites its kept entry. `fill` updates only paths still kept, so an edit that evicted a module in the meantime never resurrects it.

=>

export class LoomMemo extends Effect.Service<LoomMemo>()('LoomMemo', {
  effect: Effect.gen(function* () {
    const state = yield* SynchronizedRef.make<MemoState>(empty)

    return {
      get: (
        path: Path,
        build: Effect.Effect<LoomModule>,
      ): Effect.Effect<LoomModule> =>
        SynchronizedRef.modifyEffect(state, (s) =>
          Option.match(Option.fromNullable(s.modules.get(path)), {
            onSome: (module) =>
              Effect.succeed([module, { ...s, hits: s.hits + 1 }] as const),
            onNone: () =>
              Effect.map(build, (module) => [
                module,
                {
                  ...s,
                  misses: s.misses + 1,
                  modules: new Map(s.modules).set(path, module),
                },
              ] as const),
          }),
        ),

      entries: SynchronizedRef.get(state).pipe(Effect.map((s) => s.modules)),

      fill: (produced: ReadonlyMap<Path, LoomModule>): Effect.Effect<void> =>
        SynchronizedRef.update(state, (s) => ({
          ...s,
          modules: new Map(
            Array.map(
              Array.fromIterable(s.modules),
              ([path, kept]) => [path, produced.get(path) ?? kept] as const,
            ),
          ),
        })),

      evict: (paths: Iterable<Path>): Effect.Effect<void> => {
        const drop = new Set(paths)
        return SynchronizedRef.update(state, (s) => ({
          ...s,
          modules: new Map(
            pipe(
              Array.fromIterable(s.modules),
              Array.filter(([path]) => !drop.has(path)),
            ),
          ),
        }))
      },

      stats: SynchronizedRef.get(state).pipe(
        Effect.map(
          (s): MemoStats => ({
            hits: s.hits,
            misses: s.misses,
            size: s.modules.size,
          }),
        ),
      ),
    }
  }),
}) {}

## What this module draws on

Effect supplies `SynchronizedRef` for the atomic state, and `Array`, `Option`, and `pipe` for the operations. `LoomModule` and `Path` from the corpus model are what it caches and keys by.

=>

import { Array, Effect, Option, SynchronizedRef, pipe } from 'effect'
import { type LoomModule, type Path } from '@athrio/loom-ast/LoomCorpusAst'

